<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Received 2020 Aug 31; Accepted 2021 Mar 15; Issue date 2021 Jul.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>© 2021 by the Association of Bone and Joint
Surgeons</div>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC8208387  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33929986/" class="usa-link">33929986</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>See "<a href="/articles/PMC8208376/" class="usa-link"><em>CORR</em> Insights®: Is D-dimer a Reliable Serum Marker for Shoulder Periprosthetic Joint Infection?</a>" on page 1455.</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="sec1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Background</h3>
<p>The diagnosis of periprosthetic shoulder infection continues to be difficult
to make with confidence. Serum D-dimer has proven to be effective as a
screening tool for periprosthetic joint infection in other major joints;
however, it has yet to be evaluated for use in periprosthetic shoulder
infection.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Questions/purposes</h3>
<p>(1) Is D-dimer elevated in patients with probable or definite periprosthetic
shoulder infections? (2) What is the diagnostic accuracy of D-dimer for
periprosthetic shoulder infections? (3) What are the diagnostic accuracies
of serum tests (erythrocyte sedimentation rate [ESR], C-reactive protein
[CRP], and D-dimer), singly and in combination?</p></section><section id="sec3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h3>
<p>Between March 2016 and March 2020, 94 patients undergoing revision total
shoulder arthroplasty (anatomic or reverse) at a single institution had
preoperative serum testing with CRP, ESR, and D-dimer. These 94 patients
were a subset of 189 revision shoulder arthroplasties performed at this
institution during the study period who met inclusion criteria and consented
to participate. Included patients had a mean ± SD age of 69 ± 8
years, and 56% (53 of 94) were men. Patient records were reviewed to
classify patients as definitely having infection, probably having infection,
possibly having infection, or unlikely to have an infection, according to
the International Consensus Meeting (ICM) definition of periprosthetic
shoulder infection. Statistical analyses, including a receiver operating
characteristic curve analysis, were performed to quantify the diagnostic
value of D-dimer for periprosthetic shoulder infection. Based on the ICM
definition, 4% (4 of 94), 15% (14 of 94), 14% (13 of 94), and 67% (63 of 94)
of patients had definite, probable, possible, or unlikely periprosthetic
shoulder infections.</p></section><section id="sec4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h3>
<p>D-dimer was elevated in patients with definite or probable infections (median
[range] 661 ng/mL [150 to 8205]) compared with those with possible
infections or those who were unlikely to have an infection (263 ng/mL [150
to 3060]; median difference 143 ng/mL [95% CI 40 to 503]; p = 0.01). In
the receiver operating characteristic curve analysis, D-dimer had an area
under the curve of 0.71 (0.50-0.92), demonstrating weak diagnostic value. A
D-dimer level of 598 ng/mL provided a sensitivity and specificity of 61%
(95% CI 36% to 82%) and 74% (95% CI 62% to 83%), respectively, for
diagnosing a definite or probable infection according to the ICM
definitions. The specificity of detecting periprosthetic joint infection
(88% [95% CI 79% to 94%]) was high when three positive serum markers (ESR,
CRP, and D-dimer) were required, at the expense of sensitivity (28% [95% CI
10% to 53%]).</p></section><section id="sec5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h3>
<p>In periprosthetic shoulder infection, D-dimer is elevated. However, similar
to other serum tests, it has limited diagnostic utility in identifying
patients with periprosthetic shoulder infection. Further work is needed to
understand the process by which D-dimer is associated with active
infection.</p></section><section id="sec6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Level of Evidence</h3>
<p>Level III, diagnostic study.</p></section></section><section id="s1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p>Accurate diagnosis of periprosthetic joint infection (PJI) of the shoulder remains
elusive [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>, <a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>, <a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>, <a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>]. Identifying
shoulder PJI is complicated by the lack of a strong inflammatory response typically
seen in PJI of the hip and knee [<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>, <a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">33</a>] and the ambiguous clinical importance of
frequent isolation of <em>Cutibacterium acnes</em> from intraoperative
cultures [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>]. Because culture results may not be known for 2 weeks after revision
surgery, reliable serum markers of infection are attractive for screening for PJI
before surgery. The erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and C-reactive protein
(CRP) obtained from the serum serve as more reliable screening tools for PJI after
lower extremity arthroplasty [<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>, <a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>, <a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31</a>];
however, these tools lack sensitivity in detecting shoulder PJI [<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>]. Furthermore, joint aspiration, a reliable
marker of lower extremity PJI [<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>, <a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>, <a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">34</a>],
has shown poor sensitivity in the shoulder [<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>]. Many authors have demonstrated culture positivity for <em>C.
acnes</em> in presumed aseptic revision total shoulder arthroplasty with
unknown clinical relevance [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>, <a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a>].
In 2018, the shoulder subgroup of the International Consensus Meeting (ICM) on
musculoskeletal infection provided a definition for shoulder PJI [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>]. Although consensus-based and untested,
this definition provides the shoulder arthroplasty community with a uniform
definition of shoulder PJI to provide consistency across research efforts.</p>
<p>To improve the screening tools for PJI, authors have investigated the use of existing
tests that may be associated with PJI. This has included D-dimer—a fibrin
degradation product more commonly associated with screening for pulmonary embolism
[<a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a>]. It has been suggested that the
increased fibrinolytic activity may be as a result of sequestration of infecting
organisms to the joint through coagulation. D-dimer is simply an easily quantifiable
measure of the extent of fibrinolytic activity. Shahi et al. [<a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>] studied the utility of D-dimer to assess PJI of the lower
extremity. Using a strict PJI definition, they found that a serum D-dimer level
above 850 ng/mL had a sensitivity and specificity of 89% and 93%, respectively, for
detecting PJI in the lower extremity. Although novel in its application to PJI,
their finding is not without precedent. Rodelo et al. [<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a>] identified D-dimer as a marker of 28-day mortality in
patients admitted with presumed sepsis. Furthermore, in a septic arthritis model of
foals, Ribera et al. [<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a>] demonstrated that
the synovial fluid’s concentration of D-dimer was elevated in patients with
septic arthritis.</p>
<p>The pathologic process associated with periprosthetic shoulder infection is unique
and not fully understood. With a high prevalence of nonvirulent infecting organisms,
novel markers such as D-dimer may serve as a better indication of occult
infections.</p>
<p>Therefore, we asked:(1) Is D-dimer elevated in patients with probable or definite
periprosthetic shoulder infections? (2) What is the diagnostic accuracy of D-dimer
for periprosthetic shoulder infections? (3) What are the diagnostic accuracies of
serum tests (ESR, CRP, and D-dimer), singly and in combination?</p></section><section id="s2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Patients and Methods</h2>
<p>After local institutional review board approval, this study was undertaken. All
patients undergoing revision shoulder arthroplasty between March 2016 and March 2020
at a single institution were potential candidates for this study. During that
period, 189 patients underwent revision total shoulder arthroplasty for any
indication other than reimplantation as part of two-stage surgery. Patients with an
active ulcer, history of recent trauma (within 2 weeks), systemic inflammatory
diseases requiring pharmacologic treatment, prior surgery within 30 days, and
hypercoagulation disorders were excluded. In addition, any patients who underwent
revision procedures for which intraoperative cultures were not taken were excluded
(n = 4). In all, 118 patients not meeting these exclusion criteria had
preoperative ESR, CRP, or D-dimer serum studies obtained on the day of surgery. Of
these, 94 patients had results from preoperative D-dimer testing. The patients had a
mean ± SD age of 69 ± 8 years, 56% (53 of 94) were men, and 4% (4 of 94)
patients had undergone prior surgery within the past 3 months.</p>
<p>During the study period, a standardized culturing technique was used, and tissue was
taken from the anterior capsule, inferior capsule, glenoid, humeral canal, and
underneath the prosthetic humeral head using fresh instruments. All culture
specimens were sent to a single institutional microbiology laboratory where aerobic
and anaerobic media were used, and cultures were held for 14 days. Clinical
presentations and laboratory data were used to classify patients as having an
unlikely, possible, probable, or definite shoulder PJI based on the 2018 ICM
criteria for shoulder PJI [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>]. All patients
classified as having a definitive or probable shoulder PJI were classified as having
a PJI. All patients classified as having a possible or unlikely PJI were classified
as aseptic. A patient was considered as definitely having PJI if he or she had a
sinus tract, gross intraarticular purulence, or two positive cultures with
phenotypically identical virulent organisms. Otherwise, positive diagnostic test
results or clinical findings were assigned a weight (Table <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">1</a>), and a patient was categorized as having a probable infection
if there was a positive culture result and a summed weight of at least 6 points. A
patient was classified as having a possible infection if they had at least 6 points
without positive cultures, had less than 6 points with a single positive culture
with a virulent organism, or had less than 6 points with two positive cultures with
nonvirulent organisms. A patient was classified as unlikely to be infected if they
had less than 6 points and negative cultures or a single positive culture with
low-virulent organism. Preoperative aspiration was not performed frequently in this
cohort, and when performed, most often resulted in a dry aspiration. Furthermore,
frozen sectioning is not performed routinely at our institution. Three patients in
this cohort did not have an ESR result and a single patient did not have a CRP
result. If a test was not performed as part of the work-up for infection, it was
assumed to be negative for the purposes of this research. Forty-one percent (39 of
94) of patients had positive intraoperative culture results. Nearly two-thirds (64%
[25 of 39]) of the positive cultures grew <em>Cutibacterium acnes</em>. The
remaining positive cultures were <em>Staphylococcus epidermidis</em> (n
= 4), methicillin-resistant <em>Staphylococcus aureus</em> (n =
3), non-speciated Bacillus (n = 4), <em>Streptococcus mitis</em> (n
= 1), <em>Enterobacter clocae</em> (n = 1), coagulase-negative
Staphylococcus (n = 1), <em>Streptococcus agalactiae</em> (n = 1),
and <em>Corynebacterium striatum</em> (n = 1). Two cultures had
polymicrobial growth. Sixty-seven percent (63 of 94) of patients who underwent
revisions were classified as unlikely to be infected, according to the ICM
criteria.</p>
