<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p>To develop diagnostic thresholds and understand the diagnostic utility of the
inflammatory tests, we performed a receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve
analysis. The threshold was calculated using the Youden statistic. This was
performed even for previously tested inflammatory tests (ESR and CRP) that have
thresholds developed from evidence in the lower extremity. Based on the thresholds
calculated from the ROC curve analysis, the sensitivity, specificity, positive
predictive value (PPV), negative predictive value (NPV), and accuracy were
determined and are reported.</p>
<p>After defining the diagnostic thresholds, we established the improvement in
diagnostic accuracy through a combination of serum tests. First, the sensitivity,
specificity, and accuracy using the ICM definition were determined if both ESR and
CRP were required to be positive. We then ascertained the diagnostic accuracy of CRP
and D-dimer combined and that of ESR and CRP combined. Finally, the diagnostic
accuracy of all three positive tests was determined.</p>
<p>Although sensitivity and specificity are independent of cohort disease prevalence, it
is important to recall that NPV and PPV are not. In this cohort, 4% (4 of 94), 15%
(14 of 94), 14% (13 of 94), and 67% (63 of 94) of patients were classified as having
definite, probable, possible, or unlikely periprosthetic shoulder infections based
on the ICM definition of periprosthetic shoulder infection.</p>
<section id="s2-1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Ethical Approval</h3>
<p>Ethical approval for this study was obtained from the Office of Human Research
Institutional Review Board of Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA,
USA.</p></section><section id="s2-2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical Analysis</h3>
<p>To confirm normality of the data distribution, skewness and kurtosis thresholds
of two and 12 were used, respectively. To compare the D-dimer level and levels
of other inflammatory markers between groups, we used a t-test for parametric
data and the Wilcoxon rank-sum test for nonparametric data. Effect size was
represented with mean difference for parametric data and median difference as
estimated by the Hodges-Lehmann estimator for nonparametric data. To assess two
continuous variables, we used the Pearson correlation coefficient. The analysis
was performed in SPSS version 27 (IBM).</p></section></section><section id="s3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<section id="s3-1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">D-dimer Levels in Patients with Probable or Definite Infection</h3>
<p>The D-dimer level in patients classified as having a probable or definite
infection (median [range] 661 ng/mL [150 to 8205]) was higher than in those
classified as having an unlikely or possible infection (263 ng/mL [150 to 3060];
median difference 143 ng/mL [95% CI 40 to 503]; p = 0.01) (Table <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">2</a>). This difference was less pronounced for
ESR (mean 36 mm/hour [95% CI 24 to 47] versus 30 mm/hour [95% CI 23 to 36]; p
= 0.41) and CRP (median 1.0 mg/dL [95% CI 0.4 to 2.0] versus 0.4 mg/dL [95%
CI 0.3 to 0.7]; p = 0.02). Patients with positive culture results did not
have an elevated D-dimer level (median 289 ng/mL [150 to 8205]) compared with
those with negative culture results (313 ng/mL [150 to 2787]; p = 0.37). As
well, among patients with positive cultures, D-dimer was statistically similar
if the culture was positive for <em>C. acnes</em> (median 246 ng/mL [150
to 3060]) or another organism (median 638 ng/mL [150 to 8205]; p = 0.09).
Among patients with <em>C. acnes</em>–positive cultures, those
who met the definition of infection according to the ICM criteria had a
statistically similar D-dimer level compared with those considered to have a low
likelihood of infection (598 ng/dL [201 to 943] versus 221 [150 to 3060] ng/mL;
median difference 104 [95% CI -29 to 530]; p = 0.09). In the <em>C.
acnes–</em>positive population, the CRP level was elevated (1.0
mg/dL [0.3 to 7.4] versus 0.3 mg/dL [0.1 to 2.5]; median difference 0.6 [95% CI
0.0 to 1.5]; p = 0.04) in patients classified as infected (Table <a href="#T3" class="usa-link">3</a>).</p>
