<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="s3-2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Diagnostic Accuracy of D-Dimer for Shoulder PJI</h3>
<p>A D-dimer threshold of 598 ng/mL was the threshold for predicting probable or
definite PJI, with a sensitivity and specificity of 61% (95% CI 36% to 82%) and
74% (95% CI 62% to 83%), respectively (Table <a href="#T4" class="usa-link">4</a>). When including only patients with cultures positive for
<em>C. acnes</em>, two thresholds were identified for D-dimer as
predictive of probable infection: 270 ng/mL (higher sensitivity) and 598 ng/mL
(higher specificity). In this cohort, a CRP level greater than 0.8 mg/dL
provided the greatest diagnostic accuracy (area under the curve 0.76) in
diagnosing infection.</p>
