<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="fn3"><p>An increased number of tests with positive results (ESR, CRP, or
D-dimer) improves specificity at the cost of sensitivity.</p></div></div></section></section></section><section id="s4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>Although the diagnosis of lower extremity PJI generally can be made with confidence
[<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>], accurately diagnosing shoulder
infection remains a challenge [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>]. The
difficulty arises from the low sensitivity of serum markers [<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>, <a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>], limited utility
of synovial fluid aspiration [<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>], and the
confounding results of frequently positive culture results in known aseptic settings
[<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>, <a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>, <a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a>]. Recent evidence has
evaluated D-dimer as a diagnostic tool for lower extremity PJI with some promising
results [<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>, <a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>]. Given the persistent ambiguity in diagnosing periprosthetic
shoulder infection and the poor performance screening studies, this study was
designed to investigate the utility of D-dimer for diagnosing shoulder PJI.
Unfortunately, D-dimer was not substantially better than ESR or CRP in diagnosing
PJI. Although, the addition of D-dimer in combination with ESR and CRP improves the
overall sensitivity of detecting shoulder PJI, it does so at the expense of
specificity.</p>
<section id="s4-1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Limitations</h3>
<p>The results of this study must be considered in light of its limitations. First,
similar to all studies of shoulder PJI, this analysis lacks a gold-standard
definition of PJI. To resolve this, we used an evidence-based definition of
shoulder PJI provided by the ICM on musculoskeletal infections [<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>]. Although formed by an expert panel
with a heavy reliance on the existing evidence, this definition has not been
stringently tested. Given the lack of a true “gold-standard” test
for shoulder PJI against which to test any proposed definition, and with discord
in the community regarding the diagnosis of shoulder PJI, the definition
provided by the ICM serves as the optimal method for providing consensus among
the community. Second, this analysis excluded patients in the acute
postoperative period (within 30 days) and those with inflammatory conditions
that could elevate D-dimer levels irrespective of PJI. Although this exclusion
criterion removes potential bias, it does not allow for an evaluation of the use
of D-dimer in such patients. Third, this study did not evaluate other potential
markers of PJI such as synovial fluid, leukocyte esterase, alpha-defensin, or
frozen sections. These markers are supported only by inconsistent evidence for
use in diagnosing shoulder PJI [<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>, <a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">35</a>, <a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">35</a>]; however, their use in this study may have provided a more
complete clinical picture of patients’ infection status. In the absence
of these tests, and in a few cases serum tests, the results were considered to
be negative. The application of the results in this manner likely had little
impact on the results of this analysis given the design of the definition for
shoulder PJI. During development of the definition, the creators intended such
application given the aggregate point system and inclusion of infrequently
performed tests. Fourth, ESR and CRP are components of the ICM definition, and
their inclusion may improve their accuracy when each measure is analyzed.
However, despite the inclusion of ESR in this analysis, its diagnostic accuracy
was minimal. Fifth, in specific instances, D-dimer demonstrated large
differences in median results between groups without statistical significance.
This may represent a Type II error as a result of small sample size. Future work
will be necessary to determine whether the trends observed here are valid.
Regardless, this should not affect the assessment of the diagnostic rigor of
D-dimer, ESR, and CRP.</p></section><section id="s4-2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Using D-dimer to Diagnose Shoulder PJI</h3>
<p>Although there is a clear association between periprosthetic shoulder infection
and elevated D-dimer levels, the diagnostic utility of D-dimer may be limited.
Consistent with other studies, we found that ESR and CRP—common
diagnostic tools for lower extremity PJI with sensitivity over 90% and
specificity often approaching 80% [<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>,
<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>, <a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a>] —have limited diagnostic utility in diagnosing shoulder
PJI [<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>]. Villacis et al. [<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>] and Grosso et al. [<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>] explored serum IL-6 in revision
shoulder arthroplasty as an alternative to ESR and CRP, but they demonstrated
that these tools were less effective than standard inflammatory markers for
diagnosing shoulder PJI. The definition of PJI provided by the ICM [<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>] is an evidence-driven, consensus-based
definition of shoulder PJI to guide clinical decisions and improve uniformity in
shoulder PJI research. Unfortunately, it is not validated, given the lack of a
gold standard for diagnosis. As such, it is unclear whether definite or probable
infection with a low D-dimer level represented a diagnosis failure or a
misclassification of infection status despite using the ICM criteria. Even so,
the diagnostic efficacy of D-dimer for shoulder PJI was similar to CRP and
improved compared with ESR (based on area under the curve). As a fibrin
degradation product, the association of D-dimer with an infectious process is
not inherent. However, this relationship has been demonstrated repeatedly [<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>, <a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a>–<a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a>, <a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>]. This cohort may have suffered from a
low sample size and potential Type II error, given the significant effects
observed that were not validated statistically. Specifically, in patients with
positive intraoperative culture for bacteria other than <em>C.
acnes</em>, the D-dimer level was elevated (not statistically) relative
to patients with cultures positive for <em>C. acnes</em>. However, when
stratifying <em>C. acnes</em> cases by ICM infection classification,
elevations of D-dimer (nonsignificant potentially due to a Type-II error) and
CRP were seen in “true” nonvirulent infections. A paramount issue
in revision shoulder arthroplasty—diagnosing an infection in the setting
of <em>C. acnes</em> growth—continues to perplex the orthopaedic
community [<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>, <a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>, <a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>, <a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>]. The interpretation of unexpected
positive culture results, especially <em>C. acnes,</em> can be
clinically challenging [<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>, <a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>]. Although the diagnostic accuracy of
D-dimer in this cohort was less than ideal, the distinction between incidental
<em>C. acnes</em> results and true <em>C. acnes</em>
infections may be possible in the future if we can develop an improved
understanding of the underlying inflammatory response detected with frequent
elevations in D-dimer levels.</p></section><section id="s4-3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Using Serum Diagnostic Tests in Combination</h3>
<p>Unfortunately, adding D-dimer as a screening tool to ESR and/or CRP improved
sensitivity but at a severe cost to specificity. To our knowledge, a published
diagnostic algorithm for work-up of suspected periprosthetic shoulder infection
does not exist. An algorithm has been previously published for lower extremity
PJI and is reliant upon use of ESR and CRP as initial screening tests [<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>, <a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>]. In hopes of improving utility of these serum tests as a screening
tool for periprosthetic shoulder infection, we aimed to test the diagnostic
accuracy of D-dimer in combination with the standard serum tests. In their
analysis, Shahi et al. [<a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>] found that
D-dimer had better diagnostic utility than ESR and CRP in combination. However,
they did not assess D-dimer in combination with ESR and CRP.</p></section><section id="s4-4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h3>
<p>In this cohort, D-dimer was elevated in cases classified as periprosthetic
shoulder infection. Unfortunately, this did not translate to a diagnostic test
that would clearly aid in the accurate diagnosis of periprosthetic shoulder
infection. Further work is needed to understand the process by which D-dimer is
associated with active infection. Such work may help to explain why some
patients with cultures positive for <em>C. acnes</em> show signs of
infection and others have no characteristics of infection. In the meantime,
D-dimer appears to do little to improve the work-up of painful shoulder
arthroplasty.</p></section></section><section id="fn-group1" class="fn-group"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Footnotes</h2>
